        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1131" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1131" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>&#8220;A question I always have when reading the virtue ethicists is where these virtues are supposed to come from.&#8221;</p>
<p>This is a great question and a too-often overlooked one. The answer, I think, is ascetic practice &#8212; fasting, almsgiving, simplicity, prayer, and so on. This was true for ancient Christian virtue ethicists, at least, and even some pagans before and during their time. Virtues, then, must be acquired by cultivating good habits. Or, from another perspective, the virtues, which are natural to us, can only be uncovered from the shadow of our passions (bad emotional habits) with daily practice. This need not be the extreme asceticism of hermits, either. Asceticism comes in degrees. Whether one can circumvent ascetic discipline with &#8220;the push of a button,&#8221; however, is a very interesting question to which I don&#8217;t have an answer.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-1132">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1132" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1132">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-1132">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1132" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1132" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Interesting point; though one wonders why the ascetic practice occurs in the first place.</p>
<p>Nassim Taleb has suggested that the ascetic practices of those world religions that have stood the test of time (in his case Greek Orthodox Christianity) have positive health consequences, which would explain perhaps why they were selected for over time. And then perhaps instilling in us the natural craving for virtue of this sort was a side-consequence.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s fun to ponder, in any case. Thanks for commenting.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-1137">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1137" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1137">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-1137">Tim</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1137" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1137" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Well maybe the virtues are just what people think they should try when something else isnt working. If you live within a highly religious culture, awesome! Premade framework for trying to make things better! Lets try that on! But in other places, they dont necessarily have that framework, so different things are tried. And the algorithms of pleasure seeking are complicated so you probably get a lot of false positives in there, which is where Id put Senecas emotion free living approach.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
            </ul>


        </div>

